  "debug_data_path": "debug_data/2020_1547",
  "eprint": {
    "title": "Two-server Distributed ORAM with Sublinear Computation and Constant Rounds",
    "authors": [
      {
        "name": "Ariel Hamlin",
        "email": "arihamlin@gmail",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Mayank Varia",
        "email": "",
        "affiliation": ""
      }
    ],
    "abstract": "Distributed ORAM (DORAM) is a multi-server variant of Oblivious RAM. Originally proposed to lower bandwidth, DORAM has recently been of great interest due to its applicability to secure computation in the RAM model, where circuit complexity and rounds of communication are equally important metrics of efficiency.\n\nIn this work, we construct the first DORAM schemes in the 2-server, semi-honest setting that simultaneously achieve sublinear server computation and constant rounds of communication.\n\nWe provide two constant-round constructions, one based on square root ORAM that has $O(\\sqrt{N}\\log N)$ local computation and another based on secure computation of a doubly efficient PIR that achieves local computation of $O(N^\\epsilon)$ for any $\\epsilon > 0$ but that allows the servers to distinguish between reads and writes.\nAs a building block in the latter construction, we provide secure computation protocols for evaluation and interpolation of multivariate polynomials based on the Fast Fourier Transform, which may be of independent interest.",
    "keywords": [
      "Distributed Oblivious RAM",
      "Square Root ORAM",
      "Doubly Efficient PIR",
      "Secure Multi- Party Computation",
      "Fast Fourier Transform"
    ],
    "category": "Cryptographic protocols",
    "publication_info": "Preprint. MINOR revision.",
    "last_updated": "2020-12-13",
    "license": "CC BY",
    "related_papers": []
  }
